"Rivière G.","A dynamical interpretation of the poleward shift of the jet streams in global warming scenarios",2011,"Journal of the Atmospheric Sciences","68","6",,"1253","1272",,,10.1175/2011JAS3641.1,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-79959647596&partnerID=40&md5=5db0ab40801390d6ebfc430991949fd0","CNRM/GAME, Météo-France/CNRS, Toulouse, France","Rivière, G., CNRM/GAME, Météo-France/CNRS, Toulouse, France","The role played by enhanced upper-tropospheric baroclinicity in the poleward shift of the jet streams in global warming scenarios is investigated. Major differences between the twentieth- and twenty-first-century simulations are first detailed using two coupled climate model outputs. There is a poleward shift of the eddydriven jets, an increase in intensity and poleward shift of the storm tracks, a strengthening of the uppertropospheric baroclinicity, and an increase in the eddy length scale. These properties are more obvious in the Southern Hemisphere. A strengthening of the poleward eddy momentum fluxes and a relative decrease in frequency of cyclonic wave breaking compared to anticyclonic wave breaking events is also observed. Then, baroclinic instability in the three-level quasigeostrophic model is studied analytically and offers a simple explanation for the increased eddy spatial scale. It is shown that if the potential vorticity gradient changes its sign below the midlevel (i.e., if the critical level is located in the lower troposphere as in the real atmosphere), long and short wavelengths become respectively more and less unstable when the uppertropospheric baroclinicity is increased. Finally, a simple dry atmospheric general circulation model (GCM) is used to confirm the key role played by the upper-level baroclinicity by employing a normal-mode approach and long-term simulations forced by a temperature relaxation. The eddy length scale is shown to largely determine the nature of the breaking: long (short) wavelengths break more anticyclonically (cyclonically). When the upper-tropospheric baroclinicity is reinforced, long wavelengths become more unstable, break more strongly anticyclonically, and push the jet more poleward. Short wavelengths being less unstable, they are less efficient in pushing the jet equatorward. This provides an interpretation for the increased poleward eddy momentum fluxes and thus the poleward shift of the eddy-driven jets. © 2011 American Meteorological Society.","Baroclinic flows; Coupled models; Dynamics; Eddies; Global warming; Jets","Atmospheric general circulation models; Baroclinic flows; Baroclinic instability; Baroclinicity; Coupled climate model; Coupled models; Critical level; Dynamical interpretation; Eddies; Eddy momentum flux; Jet streams; Length scale; Long term simulation; Long wavelength; Lower troposphere; Poleward shift; Potential vorticity gradients; Quasi-geostrophic model; Short wavelengths; Southern Hemisphere; Spatial scale; Storm track; Temperature relaxation; Three-level; Wavebreaking; Computer simulation; Global warming; Meteorology; Momentum; Oceanography; Strengthening (metal); Troposphere; Climate models; anticyclone; atmosphere-ocean coupling; atmospheric general circulation model; baroclinic mode; baroclinic motion; eddy; jet; potential vorticity; Southern Hemisphere; troposphere; twentieth century; twenty first century; wave breaking",,,,,,"Balasubramanian, G., Garner, S., The equilibration of short baroclinic waves (1997) J. Atmos. Sci., 54, pp. 2850-2871; Balasubramanian, G., Garner, S., The role of momentum fluxes in shaping the life cycle of a baroclinic wave (1997) J. Atmos. Sci., 54, pp. 510-533; Chen, G., Held, I., Phase speed spectra and the recent poleward shift of southern hemisphere surface westerlies (2007) Geophys. Res. Lett., 34, pp. L21805. , doi:10.1029/2007GL031200; Chen, G., Held, I., Robinson, W., Sensitivity of the latitude of the surface westerlies to surface friction (2007) J. Atmos. Sci., 64, pp. 2899-2915; Chen, G., Lu, J., Frierson, D., Phase speed spectra and the latitude of surface westerlies: Interannual variability and global warming trend (2008) J. Climate, 21, pp. 5942-5959; Davey, M., Baroclinic instability in a fluid with three layers (1977) J. Atmos. Sci., 34, pp. 1224-1234; Fraedrich, K., Kirk, E., Luksh, U., Lunkeit, F., The Portable University Model of the Atmosphere (PUMA): Storm track dynamics and low-frequency variability (2005) Meteor. Z., 14, pp. 735-745; Frierson, D.M.W., Robust increases in midlatitude static stability in simulations of global warming (2006) Geophys. Res. Lett., 33, pp. L24816. , doi:10.1029/2006GL027504; Frisius, T., Lunkeit, F., Fraedrich, K., James, I., Stormtrack organization and variability in a simplified atmospheric global circulation model (1998) Quart. J. Roy. Meteor. Soc., 124, pp. 1019-1043; Geng, Q., Sugi, M., Possible change of extratropical cyclone activity due to enhanced greenhouse gases and sulfate aerosols study with a high-resolution AGCM (2003) J. Climate, 16, pp. 2262-2274; Haigh, J.D., Blackburn, M., Day, R., The response of tropospheric circulation to perturbations in lower-stratospheric temperature (2005) J. Climate, 18, pp. 3672-3685; Hall, N., Hoskins, B.J., Valdes, P., Senior, C.A., Stormtracks in a high-resolutionGCMwith doubled carbon dioxide (1994) Quart. J. Roy. Meteor. Soc., 120, pp. 1209-1230; Hartmann, D., Zuercher, P., Response of baroclinic life cycles to barotropic shear (1998) J. Atmos. Sci., 55, pp. 297-313; Held, I., Suarez, M., A proposal for the intercomparison of the dynamical cores of atmospheric general circulation models (1994) Bull. Amer. Meteor. Soc., 75, pp. 1825-1830; Hoskins, B.J., Intyre, M.E.M., Robertson, R.W., On the use and significance of isentropic potential vorticity maps (1985) Quart. J. Roy. Meteor. Soc., 111, pp. 877-946; Kidston, J., Dean, S., Renwick, J., Vallis, G.K., A robust increase in the eddy length scale in the simulation of future climates (2010) Geophys. Res. Lett., 37, 